description: Composite numbers not ending in zero that yield a prime when turned upside down.
links: Reinhard Zumkeller, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1048 (all terms < 1000000)
example: 68 is not prime, yet when turned upside down gives 89 which is prime.
prog: (Haskell)import Data.List (intersect)import Numeric (readInt)import Data.Char (digitToInt)a048889 n = a048889_list !! (n-1)a048889_list = filter f a002808_list where   f n = n `mod` 10 > 0 &&         null ("23547" `intersect` show n)  &&         (a010051 (fst $ head $ readInt 10 (const True) ud $ ns) == 1)       where ns = reverse $ show n             ud '6' = 9             ud '9' = 6             ud z = digitToInt z-- _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 11 2011
